#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:3
msgid "The writing and reporting of assertions in tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:11
msgid "Asserting with the ``assert`` statement"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:13
msgid ""
"``pytest`` allows you to use the standard python ``assert`` for verifying "
"expectations and values in Python tests.  For example, you can write the "
"following::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:17
msgid ""
"# content of test_assert1.py\n"
"def f():\n"
"    return 3\n"
"\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    assert f() == 4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:24
msgid ""
"to assert that your function returns a certain value. If this assertion "
"fails you will see the return value of the function call::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:27
msgid ""
"$ py.test test_assert1.py\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 1 items\n"
"\n"
"test_assert1.py F\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_function ________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_function():\n"
">       assert f() == 4\n"
"E       assert 3 == 4\n"
"E        +  where 3 = f()\n"
"\n"
"test_assert1.py:5: AssertionError\n"
"======= 1 failed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:46
msgid ""
"``pytest`` has support for showing the values of the most common "
"subexpressions including calls, attributes, comparisons, and binary and "
"unary operators. (See :ref:`tbreportdemo`).  This allows you to use the "
"idiomatic python constructs without boilerplate code while not losing "
"introspection information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:52
msgid "However, if you specify a message with the assertion like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:54
msgid "assert a % 2 == 0, \"value was odd, should be even\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:56
msgid ""
"then no assertion introspection takes places at all and the message will be "
"simply shown in the traceback."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:59
msgid ""
"See :ref:`assert-details` for more information on assertion introspection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:64
msgid "Assertions about expected exceptions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:66
msgid ""
"In order to write assertions about raised exceptions, you can use ``pytest."
"raises`` as a context manager like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:69
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"def test_zero_division():\n"
"    with pytest.raises(ZeroDivisionError):\n"
"        1 / 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:75
msgid ""
"and if you need to have access to the actual exception info you may use::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:77
msgid ""
"def test_recursion_depth():\n"
"    with pytest.raises(RuntimeError) as excinfo:\n"
"        def f():\n"
"            f()\n"
"        f()\n"
"    assert 'maximum recursion' in str(excinfo.value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:84
msgid ""
"``excinfo`` is a ``ExceptionInfo`` instance, which is a wrapper around the "
"actual exception raised.  The main attributes of interest are ``.type``, ``."
"value`` and ``.traceback``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:88
msgid ""
"If you want to write test code that works on Python 2.4 as well, you may "
"also use two other ways to test for an expected exception::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:91
msgid ""
"pytest.raises(ExpectedException, func, *args, **kwargs)\n"
"pytest.raises(ExpectedException, \"func(*args, **kwargs)\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:94
msgid ""
"both of which execute the specified function with args and kwargs and "
"asserts that the given ``ExpectedException`` is raised.  The reporter will "
"provide you with helpful output in case of failures such as *no exception* "
"or *wrong exception*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:99
msgid ""
"Note that it is also possible to specify a \"raises\" argument to ``pytest."
"mark.xfail``, which checks that the test is failing in a more specific way "
"than just having any exception raised::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:103
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail(raises=IndexError)\n"
"def test_f():\n"
"    f()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:107
msgid ""
"Using ``pytest.raises`` is likely to be better for cases where you are "
"testing exceptions your own code is deliberately raising, whereas using "
"``@pytest.mark.xfail`` with a check function is probably better for "
"something like documenting unfixed bugs (where the test describes what "
"\"should\" happen) or bugs in dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:117
msgid "Assertions about expected warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:121
msgid ""
"You can check that code raises a particular warning using :ref:`pytest.warns "
"<warns>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:128
msgid "Making use of context-sensitive comparisons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:132
msgid ""
"``pytest`` has rich support for providing context-sensitive information when "
"it encounters comparisons.  For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:135
msgid ""
"# content of test_assert2.py\n"
"\n"
"def test_set_comparison():\n"
"    set1 = set(\"1308\")\n"
"    set2 = set(\"8035\")\n"
"    assert set1 == set2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:142
msgid "if you run this module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:144
msgid ""
"$ py.test test_assert2.py\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 1 items\n"
"\n"
"test_assert2.py F\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_set_comparison ________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_set_comparison():\n"
"        set1 = set(\"1308\")\n"
"        set2 = set(\"8035\")\n"
">       assert set1 == set2\n"
"E       assert {'0', '1', '3', '8'} == {'0', '3', '5', '8'}\n"
"E         Extra items in the left set:\n"
"E         '1'\n"
"E         Extra items in the right set:\n"
"E         '5'\n"
"E         Use -v to get the full diff\n"
"\n"
"test_assert2.py:5: AssertionError\n"
"======= 1 failed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:169
msgid "Special comparisons are done for a number of cases:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:171
msgid "comparing long strings: a context diff is shown"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:172
msgid "comparing long sequences: first failing indices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:173
msgid "comparing dicts: different entries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:175
msgid "See the :ref:`reporting demo <tbreportdemo>` for many more examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:178
msgid "Defining your own assertion comparison"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:180
msgid ""
"It is possible to add your own detailed explanations by implementing the "
"``pytest_assertrepr_compare`` hook."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/hookspec.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.hookspec.pytest_assertrepr_compare:1
msgid "return explanation for comparisons in failing assert expressions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/hookspec.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.hookspec.pytest_assertrepr_compare:3
msgid ""
"Return None for no custom explanation, otherwise return a list of strings.  "
"The strings will be joined by newlines but any newlines *in* a string will "
"be escaped.  Note that all but the first line will be indented sligthly, the "
"intention is for the first line to be a summary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:185
msgid ""
"As an example consider adding the following hook in a conftest.py which "
"provides an alternative explanation for ``Foo`` objects::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:188
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"from test_foocompare import Foo\n"
"def pytest_assertrepr_compare(op, left, right):\n"
"    if isinstance(left, Foo) and isinstance(right, Foo) and op == \"==\":\n"
"        return ['Comparing Foo instances:',\n"
"                '   vals: %s != %s' % (left.val, right.val)]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:195
msgid "now, given this test module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:197
msgid ""
"# content of test_foocompare.py\n"
"class Foo:\n"
"    def __init__(self, val):\n"
"        self.val = val\n"
"\n"
"    def __eq__(self, other):\n"
"        return self.val == other.val\n"
"\n"
"def test_compare():\n"
"    f1 = Foo(1)\n"
"    f2 = Foo(2)\n"
"    assert f1 == f2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:210
msgid ""
"you can run the test module and get the custom output defined in the "
"conftest file::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:213
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q test_foocompare.py\n"
"F\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_compare ________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_compare():\n"
"        f1 = Foo(1)\n"
"        f2 = Foo(2)\n"
">       assert f1 == f2\n"
"E       assert Comparing Foo instances:\n"
"E            vals: 1 != 2\n"
"\n"
"test_foocompare.py:11: AssertionError\n"
"1 failed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:232
msgid "Advanced assertion introspection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:237
msgid ""
"Reporting details about a failing assertion is achieved either by rewriting "
"assert statements before they are run or re-evaluating the assert expression "
"and recording the intermediate values. Which technique is used depends on "
"the location of the assert, ``pytest`` configuration, and Python version "
"being used to run ``pytest``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:243
msgid ""
"By default, ``pytest`` rewrites assert statements in test modules. Rewritten "
"assert statements put introspection information into the assertion failure "
"message. ``pytest`` only rewrites test modules directly discovered by its "
"test collection process, so asserts in supporting modules which are not "
"themselves test modules will not be rewritten."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:251
msgid ""
"``pytest`` rewrites test modules on import. It does this by using an import "
"hook to write a new pyc files. Most of the time this works transparently. "
"However, if you are messing with import yourself, the import hook may "
"interfere. If this is the case, simply use ``--assert=reinterp`` or ``--"
"assert=plain``. Additionally, rewriting will fail silently if it cannot "
"write new pycs, i.e. in a read-only filesystem or a zipfile."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:258
msgid ""
"If an assert statement has not been rewritten or the Python version is less "
"than 2.6, ``pytest`` falls back on assert reinterpretation. In assert "
"reinterpretation, ``pytest`` walks the frame of the function containing the "
"assert statement to discover sub-expression results of the failing assert "
"statement. You can force ``pytest`` to always use assertion reinterpretation "
"by passing the ``--assert=reinterp`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:265
msgid ""
"Assert reinterpretation has a caveat not present with assert rewriting: If "
"evaluating the assert expression has side effects you may get a warning that "
"the intermediate values could not be determined safely.  A common example of "
"this issue is an assertion which reads from a file::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:270
msgid "assert f.read() != '...'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:272
msgid ""
"If this assertion fails then the re-evaluation will probably succeed! This "
"is because ``f.read()`` will return an empty string when it is called the "
"second time during the re-evaluation.  However, it is easy to rewrite the "
"assertion and avoid any trouble::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:277
msgid ""
"content = f.read()\n"
"assert content != '...'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:280
msgid ""
"All assert introspection can be turned off by passing ``--assert=plain``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:282
msgid ""
"For further information, Benjamin Peterson wrote up `Behind the scenes of "
"pytest's new assertion rewriting <http://pybites.blogspot.com/2011/07/behind-"
"scenes-of-pytests-new-assertion.html>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:284
msgid "Add assert rewriting as an alternate introspection technique."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/assert.rst:287
msgid ""
"Introduce the ``--assert`` option. Deprecate ``--no-assert`` and ``--"
"nomagic``."
msgstr ""
